<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> First-Order LHCC </title>

	<p>
		Now that we've learned about characteristic equations, let's dive into solving some of these equations. We'll begin with first-order equations as a starting point for the higher-order equations. Recall, a first-order linear homogeneous differential equation with constant coefficients takes the form:
		<me> a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0 \qquad (a_1, a_0 \text{ constants})</me>.
		Since each term of the solution has the form <m>e^{rx}</m>, we can substitute this into our differential equation to identify the specific <m>r</m>-values for each term.
		<md>
			<mrow> a_1 \left[ e^{rx} \right]' + a_0 e^{rx} 	=\ &amp; 0									</mrow>
			<mrow> 				a_1 r e^{rx} + a_0 e^{rx}	=\ &amp; 0 									</mrow>
			<mrow> 					e^{rx} (a_1 r + a_0)	=\ &amp; 0 	\quad \left(e^{rx} \ne 0\right)	</mrow>
			<mrow> 					\us{\text{characteristic eqn}}{\ub{a_1 r + a_0	= 0}}				</mrow>
		</md>
	</p>
	
	<p>
		Solving for <m>r</m> gives the single value, <m>\ds r = -a_0/a_1 </m>, resulting in just one term in the general solution, given as follows
		<me> y = C e^{-\frac{a_0}{a_1} x} </me>.
		Now, for a few examples.
	</p>
	
	<example>
		<m>\ \ </m> Find the general solution of the equation
		<statement>
			<sidebyside>
				<p>
					<me> 3y' - 9y = 0 </me>
				</p>
				<p>
					<me> 5y' = \pi y </me>
				</p>
			</sidebyside>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				Always begin by rewriting and confirming the class of the equations,
				<sidebyside>
					<p>
						<me>
							\os{\text{LHCC}}{\ob{ y' + 9y = 0 }}
						</me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<me>
							\os{\text{LHCC}}{\ob{ 5y' - \pi y = 0 }}
						</me>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
				Now, solve the characteristic equations for <m>r</m>
				<sidebyside>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> r + 9	=\ &amp; 0 	</mrow>
							<mrow> 		r	=\ &amp; -9 </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	5r - \pi	=\ &amp; 0 				</mrow>
							<mrow> 			r	=\ &amp; \frac{\pi}{5}	</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
				Therefore, the <em>single</em> term general solutions are
				<sidebyside>
					<p>
						<me> y = C e^{-9x} </me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<me> y = C e^{\frac{\pi}{5}x} </me>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>
	
	<p>
		By following these steps, we can solve any first-order LHCC equation using the characteristic equation. This method is not only straightforward but also powerful, extending nicely to higher-order equations.
	</p>
	
